BiliBookLLM — Product Requirements Document (PRD)
1. Product Vision
BiliBookLLM is a lightweight, privacy-aware NotebookLLM for Bilibili video content. Users paste a Bilibili URL and receive structured, exportable notes — full transcript, chapter summaries, key takeaways, keywords, and optional Q&A — generated via an LLM-powered pipeline with a subtitle-first, local-ASR-fallback strategy.

2. Target Users
Persona	Need
Students	Distill lecture/tutorial videos into study notes
Researchers	Extract key points from long-form talks
Content curators	Quickly index and catalog video libraries
Language learners	Access bilingual transcripts for Chinese-language video
3. User Stories (MVP)
ID	Story	Priority
US-1	As a user, I can paste a Bilibili URL and see video metadata (title, thumbnail, duration) within 5 s.	P0
US-2	As a user, I can see real-time progress as the system processes my video.	P0
US-3	As a user, I can read the full timestamped transcript in a scrollable panel.	P0
US-4	As a user, I can read an overall summary, chapter summaries, key takeaways, and keywords.	P0
US-5	As a user, I can export results as Markdown, TXT, or JSON.	P0
US-6	As a user, I can view Q&A generated from the transcript.	P1
US-7	As a user, I can see which method was used (subtitle vs ASR) and confidence info.	P1
US-8	As a user, I can reprocess a video with different LLM settings.	P2
4. Functional Requirements
4.1 URL Input & Validation
Accept bilibili.com/video/BVxxxxx and b23.tv short links.
Extract BVID via regex; reject non-Bilibili URLs with clear error message.
Resolve short links to canonical BVID.
4.2 Metadata Extraction
Retrieve: title, author, thumbnail URL, duration, view count, publish date, description, page count (multi-part detection).
Display metadata card before processing begins.
4.3 Transcript Acquisition (Subtitle-First Pipeline)
Subtitle path: Query Bilibili subtitle API for CC JSON → parse into timestamped segments.
ASR fallback: Download audio via yt-dlp → convert to 16 kHz mono WAV via ffmpeg → transcribe with faster-whisper (VAD-enabled, int8 quantization).
Record which path was used in the result metadata.
4.4 Segmentation
Chunk transcript into semantically coherent segments (~500–1000 tokens).
If CC subtitles provide natural breaks (chapter markers), prefer those.
Otherwise use recursive character splitting with 10 % overlap.
4.5 LLM Summarization
Map-Reduce strategy for long transcripts:
Map: per-chunk summary.
Reduce: merge into overall summary, chapter summaries, key takeaways, keywords, Q&A.
Structured JSON output enforced via system prompt + output schema.
Configurable LLM provider (OpenAI-compatible API endpoint + model name via env vars).
4.6 Export
Markdown (.md), plain text (.txt), JSON (.json).
Markdown template with YAML front-matter (title, author, source URL, date).
5. Non-Functional Requirements
Category	Requirement
Latency	Metadata display < 5 s; subtitle extraction < 10 s; ASR ≤ 1× real-time on GPU
Scalability	Single-user MVP; architecture must support async job queue for multi-user later
Privacy	ASR runs locally; no audio sent to external services unless user opts in
Reliability	Graceful fallback: subtitle → ASR → error with clear message
Observability	Structured logging (JSON) on backend; job status exposed via API
Security	No Bilibili cookies stored in DB; env-var only. Rate-limit public endpoints
6. Out of Scope (MVP)
YouTube / other platform support
User accounts & authentication
Collaborative note editing
Real-time streaming transcription
Danmaku analysis
Mobile-native app
7. Success Metrics (Post-Launch)
Metric	Target
End-to-end processing time (10 min video, subtitle path)	< 30 s
End-to-end processing time (10 min video, ASR path)	< 15 min (CPU) / < 3 min (GPU)
Summary factual accuracy (manual spot-check)	> 85 %
Export format correctness	100 % valid Markdown/JSON



